<DOC><DOCNO> AP880715-0211 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 1929EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-15 0593</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0607</SECOND><HEAD>More Record-Breaking Heat in Midwest; Storms Around Omaha</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Temperature records continue to fall Friday in parts of theMidwest and East, and severe storms injured several people, damagedbuildings and knocked out power in the Omaha, Neb., area and partsof Florida and Michigan.   By early aftenoon, readings passing the century mark were commonacross the Arizona and California deserts, as well as portions ofIllinois, Kansas, Missouri, South Carolina and West Virginia.   The temperature reached 102 in Chicago on Friday, beating an11-year-old record by 3 degrees. Another record fell there, too: Itwas the fifth time this year that temperatures had reached tripledigits in the Windy City, more than any other year on record.   In Pittsburgh, the thermometer reached 91 degrees by earlyafternoon to make the 12th consecutive day of 90 degree or greatertemperatures. This equals the record string of 90-degree days setin July 1881.   Other temperature records were set in Eau Claire, Wis., 101,besting the 1936 record by 1 degree; La Crosse, Wis., 102, beatingthe 1931 record by 3 degrees; Madison, Wis., 98, beating the 1901record by 2 degrees; and Rockford, Ill., 101, beating the 1932record by 1 degree. Records were tied in Minneapolis-St. Paul, 101;and in Cape Hatteras, N.C., 90.   In Council Bluffs, Iowa, thunderstorms packing tornadoes causedextensive damage in a residential area. At least eight people werereported being treated at hospitals at Council Bluffs, officialssaid. Most of the injuries were described as minor.   Strong winds associated with the storms downed trees and brokewindows and wind and lightning caused scattered power outagesthroughout the Omaha metropolitan area, of which Council Bluffs isa part. A wind gust of 92 mph was reported at Omaha's EppleyAirfield, the weather service reported.   A severe thunderstorm watch continued in effect for parts ofNebraska, South Dakota, Iowa, and Missouri.   Elsewhere, heavy rain caused street flooding in parts of theFlorida panhandle early in the afternoon, and small trees, limbsand signs were reported blown down. At least two persons were hitby lightning.   Earlier Friday, strong thunderstorms, sometimes accompanied byhail, moved through northern Wisconsin and the northern half ofMichigan. One person suffered a broken leg when thunderstorm windsdowned a tree in Vilas County, Wis., the National Weather Servicesaid.   A waterspout moved onshore at St. Petersburg Beach, Fla.,causing minor roof damage to one house.   Heavier rainfall for the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included0.83 inch at Grand Island, Neb.; 0.74 inch at Green Bay, Wis.; 0.58inch at Gwinn, Mich.; 0.48 inch at Hancock, Mich.; and 0.44 inch atMarquette, Mich.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 61degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 106 degrees at Glendale, Ariz.Friday's morning low was 39 degrees at Truckee, Calif., andMissoula, Mont.   The national weather forecast for Saturday called for scatteredshowers and thunderstorms from the central and southern High Plainsthrough the middle Mississippi Valley, the Ohio Valley to themid-Atlantic Coast. The storms will be most numerous across theeastern Great Lakes and New England. Afternoon showers andthunderstorms also were forecast in much of the Southeast.   Highs above 100 were forecast across Missouri and Kansas, and inthe desert Southwest and interior valleys of California; in the 70sand 80s from the Pacific Northwest into western Montana, and fromthe northern Great Lakes into New England; and in the 90s acrossmost of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>